One of the key contradictions is between Aristotle Means' testimony that he would become an accomplice after losing his alibi due to the pre-recording, and the evidence related to the tape recorder and voiceprint analysis. The testimony claims that Juniper asked him to pre-record his speech, implying that he would not have an alibi during the time of the murder because he was supposedly in the audio room. However, the Tape Recorder evidence (Evidence 9) and the Voiceprint Analysis (Evidence 19) indicate that the recording is fake and does not have Professor Means' voice on it. This implies that his alibi could not have been compromised because he was never involved in any pre-recorded message with his voice.

Thus, while he claims that he lost his alibi because he pre-recorded a message during the time of the murder, the evidence directly contradicts this statement as no such authentic recording of him exists.

